# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: scada-security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] A **distributed control system** (**DCS**) is a computerized control system for a process or plant usually with many control loops, in which autonomous controllers are distributed throughout the system, but there is no central operator supervisory control.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] This is in contrast to systems that use centralized controllers; either discrete controllers located at a central control room or within a central computer.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The DCS concept increases reliability and reduces installation costs by localizing control functions near the process plant, with remote monitoring and supervision.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Distributed control systems first emerged in large, high value, safety critical process industries, and were attractive because the DCS manufacturer would supply both the local control level and central supervisory equipment as an integrated package, thus reducing design integration risk.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Today the functionality of Supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) and DCS systems are very similar, but DCS tends to be used on large continuous process plants where high reliability and security is important, and the control room is not necessarily geographically remote.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Many machine control systems exhibit similar properties as plant and process control systems do.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The key attribute of a DCS is its reliability due to the distribution of the control processing around nodes in the system.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] This mitigates a single processor failure.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] If a processor fails, it will only affect one section of the plant process, as opposed to a failure of a central computer which would affect the whole process.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] This distribution of computing power local to the field Input/Output (I/O) connection racks also ensures fast controller processing times by removing possible network and central processing delays.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The accompanying diagram is a general model which shows functional manufacturing levels using computerised control.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Levels 1 and 2 are the functional levels of a traditional DCS, in which all equipment are part of an integrated system from a single manufacturer.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Levels 3 and 4 are not strictly process control in the traditional sense, but where production control and scheduling takes place.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The processor nodes and operator graphical displays are connected over proprietary or industry standard networks, and network reliability is increased by dual redundancy cabling over diverse routes.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] This distributed topology also reduces the amount of field cabling by siting the I/O modules and their associated processors close to the process plant.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The processors receive information from input modules, process the information and decide control actions to be signalled by the output modules.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The field inputs and outputs can be analog signals e.g.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] 4–20 mA DC current loop or two-state signals that switch either "on" or "off", such as relay contacts or a semiconductor switch.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] DCSs are connected to sensors and actuators and use setpoint control to control the flow of material through the plant.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] A typical application is a PID controller fed by a flow meter and using a control valve as the final control element.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The DCS sends the setpoint required by the process to the controller which instructs a valve to operate so that the process reaches and stays at the desired setpoint.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Large oil refineries and chemical plants have several thousand I/O points and employ very large DCS.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Processes are not limited to fluidic flow through pipes, however, and can also include things like paper machines and their associated quality controls, variable speed drives and motor control centers, cement kilns, mining operations, ore processing facilities, and many others.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] DCSs in very high reliability applications can have dual redundant processors with "hot" switch over on fault, to enhance the reliability of the control system.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Although 4–20 mA has been the main field signalling standard, modern DCS systems can also support fieldbus digital protocols, such as Foundation Fieldbus, profibus, HART, modbus, PC Link, etc.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Modern DCSs also support neural networks and fuzzy logic applications.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Recent research focuses on the synthesis of optimal distributed controllers, which optimizes a certain H-infinity or the H 2 control criterion.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Distributed control systems (DCS) are dedicated systems used in manufacturing processes that are continuous or batch-oriented.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Process control of large industrial plants has evolved through many stages.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Initially, control would be from panels local to the process plant.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] However this required a large amount of human oversight to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently-staffed central control room.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Effectively this was the centralisation of all the localised panels, with the advantages of lower manning levels and easier overview of the process.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Often the controllers were behind the control room panels, and all automatic and manual control outputs were transmitted back to plant.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] However, whilst providing a central control focus, this arrangement was inflexible as each control loop had its own controller hardware, and continual operator movement within the control room was required to view different parts of the process.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] With the coming of electronic processors and graphic displays it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] These could be distributed around plant, and communicate with the graphic display in the control room or rooms.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The distributed control system was born.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The introduction of DCSs allowed easy interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Early minicomputers were used in the control of industrial processes since the beginning of the 1960s.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The IBM 1800, for example, was an early computer that had input/output hardware to gather process signals in a plant for conversion from field contact levels (for digital points) and analog signals to the digital domain.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The first industrial control computer system was built 1959 at the Texaco Port Arthur, Texas, refinery with an RW-300 of the Ramo-Wooldridge Company.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] In 1975, both HONEYWELL and Japanese electrical engineering firm Yokogawa introduced their own independently produced DCS's - TDC 2000 and CENTUM systems, respectively.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] US-based Bristol also introduced their UCS 3000 universal controller in 1975.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] In 1978 Valmet introduced their own DCS system called Damatic (latest web-based generation Valmet DNAe).
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] In 1980, Bailey (now part of ABB) introduced the NETWORK 90 system, Fisher Controls (now part of Emerson Electric) introduced the PROVoX system, Fischer & Porter Company (now also part of ABB) introduced DCI-4000 (DCI stands for Distributed Control Instrumentation).
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The DCS largely came about due to the increased availability of microcomputers and the proliferation of microprocessors in the world of process control.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Computers had already been applied to process automation for some time in the form of both direct digital control (DDC) and setpoint control.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] In the early 1970s Taylor Instrument Company, (now part of ABB) developed the 1010 system, Foxboro the FOX1 system, Fisher Controls the DC2 system and Bailey Controls the 1055 systems.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] All of these were DDC applications implemented within minicomputers (DEC PDP-11, Varian Data Machines, MODCOMP etc.) and connected to proprietary Input/Output hardware.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Sophisticated (for the time) continuous as well as batch control was implemented in this way.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] A more conservative approach was setpoint control, where process computers supervised clusters of analog process controllers.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] A workstation provided visibility into the process using text and crude character graphics.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Availability of a fully functional graphical user interface was a way away.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Central to the DCS model was the inclusion of control function blocks.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Function blocks evolved from early, more primitive DDC concepts of "Table Driven" software.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] One of the first embodiments of object-oriented software, function blocks were self-contained "blocks" of code that emulated analog hardware control components and performed tasks that were essential to process control, such as execution of PID algorithms.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Function blocks continue to endure as the predominant method of control for DCS suppliers, and are supported by key technologies such as Foundation Fieldbus today.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Midac Systems, of Sydney, Australia, developed an objected-oriented distributed direct digital control system in 1982.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The central system ran 11 microprocessors sharing tasks and common memory and connected to a serial communication network of distributed controllers each running two Z80s.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The system was installed at the University of Melbourne.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Digital communication between distributed controllers, workstations and other computing elements (peer to peer access) was one of the primary advantages of the DCS.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Attention was duly focused on the networks, which provided the all-important lines of communication that, for process applications, had to incorporate specific functions such as determinism and redundancy.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] As a result, many suppliers embraced the IEEE 802.4 networking standard.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] This decision set the stage for the wave of migrations necessary when information technology moved into process automation and IEEE 802.3 rather than IEEE 802.4 prevailed as the control LAN.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] In the 1980s, users began to look at DCSs as more than just basic process control.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] A very early example of a Direct Digital Control DCS was completed by the Australian business Midac in 1981–82 using R-Tec Australian designed hardware.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The system installed at the University of Melbourne used a serial communications network, connecting campus buildings back to a control room "front end".
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Each remote unit ran two Z80 microprocessors, while the front end ran eleven Z80s in a parallel processing configuration with paged common memory to share tasks and that could run up to 20,000 concurrent control objects.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] It was believed that if openness could be achieved and greater amounts of data could be shared throughout the enterprise that even greater things could be achieved.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The first attempts to increase the openness of DCSs resulted in the adoption of the predominant operating system of the day: *UNIX*.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] UNIX and its companion networking technology TCP-IP were developed by the US Department of Defense for openness, which was precisely the issue the process industries were looking to resolve.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] As a result, suppliers also began to adopt Ethernet-based networks with their own proprietary protocol layers.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The full TCP/IP standard was not implemented, but the use of Ethernet made it possible to implement the first instances of object management and global data access technology.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The 1980s also witnessed the first PLCs integrated into the DCS infrastructure.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Plant-wide historians also emerged to capitalize on the extended reach of automation systems.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The first DCS supplier to adopt UNIX and Ethernet networking technologies was Foxboro, who introduced the I/A Series system in 1987.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The drive toward openness in the 1980s gained momentum through the 1990s with the increased adoption of commercial off-the-shelf (COTS) components and IT standards.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Probably the biggest transition undertaken during this time was the move from the UNIX operating system to the Windows environment.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] While the realm of the real time operating system (RTOS) for control applications remains dominated by real time commercial variants of UNIX or proprietary operating systems, everything above real-time control has made the transition to Windows.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The introduction of Microsoft at the desktop and server layers resulted in the development of technologies such as OLE for process control (OPC), which is now a de facto industry connectivity standard.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Internet technology also began to make its mark in automation and the world, with most DCS HMI supporting Internet connectivity.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The 1990s were also known for the "Fieldbus Wars", where rival organizations competed to define what would become the IEC fieldbus standard for digital communication with field instrumentation instead of 4–20 milliamp analog communications.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The first fieldbus installations occurred in the 1990s.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Towards the end of the decade, the technology began to develop significant momentum, with the market consolidated around Ethernet I/P, Foundation Fieldbus and Profibus PA for process automation applications.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Fieldbus technics have been used to integrate machine, drives, quality and condition monitoring applications to one DCS with Valmet DNA system.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The impact of COTS, however, was most pronounced at the hardware layer.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] For years, the primary business of DCS suppliers had been the supply of large amounts of hardware, particularly I/O and controllers.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The initial proliferation of DCSs required the installation of prodigious amounts of this hardware, most of it manufactured from the bottom up by DCS suppliers.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Standard computer components from manufacturers such as Intel and Motorola, however, made it cost prohibitive for DCS suppliers to continue making their own components, workstations, and networking hardware.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] As the suppliers made the transition to COTS components, they also discovered that the hardware market was shrinking fast.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] COTS not only resulted in lower manufacturing costs for the supplier, but also steadily decreasing prices for the end users, who were also becoming increasingly vocal over what they perceived to be unduly high hardware costs.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The traditional DCS suppliers introduced new generation DCS System based on the latest Communication and IEC Standards, which resulting in a trend of combining the traditional concepts/functionalities for PLC and DCS into a one for all solution—named "Process Automation System" (PAS).
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The gaps among the various systems remain at the areas such as: the database integrity, pre-engineering functionality, system maturity, communication transparency and reliability.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] While it is expected the cost ratio is relatively the same (the more powerful the systems are, the more expensive they will be), the reality of the automation business is often operating strategically case by case.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The current next evolution step is called Collaborative Process Automation Systems.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] To compound the issue, suppliers were also realizing that the hardware market was becoming saturated.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The life cycle of hardware components such as I/O and wiring is also typically in the range of 15 to over 20 years, making for a challenging replacement market.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Many of the older systems that were installed in the 1970s and 1980s are still in use today, and there is a considerable installed base of systems in the market that are approaching the end of their useful life.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Developed industrial economies in North America, Europe, and Japan already had many thousands of DCSs installed, and with few if any new plants being built, the market for new hardware was shifting rapidly to smaller, albeit faster growing regions such as China, Latin America, and Eastern Europe.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Because of the shrinking hardware business, suppliers began to make the challenging transition from a hardware-based business model to one based on software and value-added services.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] It is a transition that is still being made today.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The applications portfolio offered by suppliers expanded considerably in the '90s to include areas such as production management, model-based control, real-time optimization, plant asset management (PAM), Real-time performance management (RPM) tools, alarm management, and many others.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] To obtain the true value from these applications, however, often requires a considerable service content, which the suppliers also provide.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Increasingly, and ironically, DCS are becoming centralised at plant level, with the ability to log into the remote equipment.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] This enables operator to control both at enterprise level ( macro ) and at the equipment level (micro), both within and outside the plant, because the importance of the physical location drops due to interconnectivity primarily thanks to wireless and remote access.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] The more wireless protocols are developed and refined, the more they are included in DCS.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] DCS controllers are now often equipped with embedded servers and provide on-the-go web access.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Whether DCS will lead Industrial Internet of Things (IIOT) or borrow key elements from remains to be seen.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] Many vendors provide the option of a mobile HMI, ready for both Android and iOS.
[src:scada-security/distributed-control-system] With these interfaces, the threat of security breaches and possible damage to plant and process are now very real.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] An **industrial control system** (**ICS**) is an electronic control system and associated instrumentation used for industrial process control.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Control systems can range in size from a few modular panel-mounted controllers to large interconnected and interactive distributed control systems (DCSs) with many thousands of field connections.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Control systems receive data from remote sensors measuring process variables (PVs), compare the collected data with desired setpoints (SPs), and derive command functions that are used to control a process through the final control elements (FCEs), such as control valves.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Larger systems are usually implemented by supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) systems, or DCSs, and programmable logic controllers (PLCs), though SCADA and PLC systems are scalable down to small systems with few control loops.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Such systems are extensively used in industries such as chemical processing, pulp and paper manufacture, power generation, oil and gas processing, and telecommunications.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] The simplest control systems are based around small discrete controllers with a single control loop each.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] These are usually panel mounted, which allows direct viewing of the front panel and provides a means of manual intervention by the operator, either to manually control the process or to change control setpoints.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Originally, these would be pneumatic controllers, a few of which are still in use, but nearly all are now electronic.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Quite complex systems can be created with networks of these controllers communicating using industry-standard protocols.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Networking allows the use of local or remote SCADA operator interfaces and enables the cascading and interlocking of controllers.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] However, as the number of control loops increases for a system design, there is a point where the use of a programmable logic controller (PLC) or distributed control system (DCS) is more manageable or cost-effective.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] A distributed control system (DCS) is a digital process control system (PCS) for a process or plant, wherein controller functions and field connection modules are distributed throughout the system.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] As the number of control loops grows, DCS becomes more cost effective than discrete controllers.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Additionally, a DCS provides supervisory viewing and management over large industrial processes.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] In a DCS, a hierarchy of controllers is connected by communication networks, allowing centralized control rooms and local on-plant monitoring and control.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] A DCS enables easy configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other computer systems such as production control.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] It also enables more sophisticated alarm handling, introduces automatic event logging, removes the need for physical records such as chart recorders and allows the control equipment to be networked and thereby located locally to the equipment being controlled to reduce cabling.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] A DCS typically uses custom-designed processors as controllers and uses either proprietary interconnections or standard protocols for communication.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Input and output modules form the peripheral components of the system.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] The processors receive information from input modules, process the information and decide control actions to be performed by the output modules.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] The input modules receive information from sensing instruments in the process (or field) and the output modules transmit instructions to the final control elements, such as control valves.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] The field inputs and outputs can either be continuously changing analog signals, e.g., current loop or 2-state signals that switch either *on* or *off*, such as relay contacts or a semiconductor switch.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Distributed control systems can normally also support Foundation Fieldbus, PROFIBUS, HART, Modbus and other digital communication buses that carry not only input and output signals but also advanced messages such as error diagnostics and status signals.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) is a control system architecture that uses computers, networked data communications and graphical user interfaces for high-level process supervisory management.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] The operator interfaces, which enable monitoring and the issuing of process commands, such as controller setpoint changes, are handled through the SCADA supervisory computer system.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] However, the real-time control logic or controller calculations are performed by networked modules which connect to other peripheral devices such as programmable logic controllers and discrete PID controllers which interface to the process plant or machinery.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] The SCADA concept was developed as a universal means of remote access to a variety of local control modules, which could be from different manufacturers, allowing access through standard automation protocols.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] In practice, large SCADA systems have grown to become very similar to distributed control systems in function, but using multiple means of interfacing with the plant.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] They can control large-scale processes that can include multiple sites and work over large distances.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] This is a commonly used architecture industrial control systems, however there are concerns about SCADA systems being vulnerable to cyberwarfare or cyberterrorism attacks.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] The SCADA software operates on a supervisory level as control actions are performed automatically by RTUs or PLCs.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] SCADA control functions are usually restricted to basic overriding or supervisory level intervention.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] A feedback control loop is directly controlled by the RTU or PLC, but the SCADA software monitors the overall performance of the loop.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] For example, a PLC may control the flow of cooling water through part of an industrial process to a set point level, but the SCADA system software will allow operators to change the set points for the flow.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] The SCADA also enables alarm conditions, such as loss of flow or high temperature, to be displayed and recorded.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] PLCs can range from small modular devices with tens of inputs and outputs (I/O) in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with a count of thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] They can be designed for multiple arrangements of digital and analog inputs and outputs, extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Initially, control was from panels local to the process plant.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] However, this required personnel to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently staffed central control room.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Often, the controllers were behind the control room panels, and all automatic and manual control outputs were individually transmitted back to the plant in the form of pneumatic or electrical signals.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Effectively, this was the centralisation of all the localised panels, with the advantages of reduced manpower requirements and a consolidated overview of the process.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] However, whilst providing a central control focus, this arrangement was inflexible as each control loop had its own controller hardware, so system changes required reconfiguration of signals by re-piping or re-wiring.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] It also required continual operator movement within a large control room in order to monitor the whole process.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] With the coming of electronic processors, high-speed electronic signalling networks and electronic graphic displays, it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] These could be distributed around the plant and would communicate with the graphic displays in the control room.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] The concept of *distributed control* was realised.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] The introduction of distributed control allowed flexible interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] For large control systems, the general commercial name *distributed control system* (DCS) was coined to refer to proprietary modular systems from many manufacturers that integrated high-speed networking and a full suite of displays and control racks.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] While the DCS was tailored to meet the needs of large continuous industrial processes, in industries where combinatorial and sequential logic was the primary requirement, the PLC evolved out of a need to replace racks of relays and timers used for event-driven control.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] The old controls were difficult to reconfigure and debug, and PLC control enabled networking of signals to a central control area with electronic displays.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] PLCs were first developed for the automotive industry on vehicle production lines, where sequential logic was becoming very complex.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] It was soon adopted in a large number of other event-driven applications as varied as printing presses and water treatment plants.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] SCADA's history is rooted in distribution applications, such as power, natural gas, and water pipelines, where there is a need to gather remote data through potentially unreliable or intermittent low-bandwidth and high-latency links.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] SCADA systems use open-loop control with sites that are widely separated geographically.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] A SCADA system uses remote terminal units (RTUs) to send supervisory data back to a control centre.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Most RTU systems always had some capacity to handle local control while the master station is not available.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] However, over the years, RTU systems have grown more and more capable of handling local control.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] The boundaries between DCS and SCADA/PLC systems are blurring as time goes on.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] The technical limits that drove the designs of these various systems are no longer as much of an issue.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Many PLC platforms can now perform quite well as a small DCS, using remote I/O and are sufficiently reliable that some SCADA systems actually manage closed-loop control over long distances.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] With the increasing speed of today's processors, many DCS products have a full line of PLC-like subsystems that weren't offered when they were initially developed.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] In 1993, with the release of IEC-1131, later to become IEC-61131-3, the industry moved towards increased code standardization with reusable, hardware-independent control software.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] For the first time, object-oriented programming (OOP) became possible within industrial control systems.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] This led to the development of both programmable automation controllers (PAC) and industrial PCs (IPC).
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] These are platforms programmed in the five standardized IEC languages: ladder logic, structured text, function block, instruction list and sequential function chart.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] They can also be programmed in modern high-level languages such as C or C++.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Additionally, they accept models developed in analytical tools such as MATLAB and Simulink.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Unlike traditional PLCs, which use proprietary operating systems, IPCs utilize Windows IoT.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] IPCs have the advantage of powerful multi-core processors with much lower hardware costs than traditional PLCs and fit well into multiple form factors such as DIN rail mount, combined with a touch-screen as a panel PC, or as an embedded PC.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] New hardware platforms and technology have contributed significantly to the evolution of DCS and SCADA systems, further blurring the boundaries and changing definitions.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] SCADA and PLCs are vulnerable to cyber attack.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] Government Joint Capability Technology Demonstration (JCTD) known as MOSAICS (More Situational Awareness for Industrial Control Systems) is the initial demonstration of cybersecurity defensive capability for critical infrastructure control systems.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] MOSAICS addresses the Department of Defense (DOD) operational need for cyber defense capabilities to defend critical infrastructure control systems from cyber attack, such as power, water and wastewater, and safety controls, affect the physical environment.
[src:scada-security/industrial-control-system] The MOSAICS JCTD prototype will be shared with commercial industry through Industry Days for further research and development, an approach intended to lead to an innovative, game-changing capabilities for cybersecurity for critical infrastructure control systems.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Modbus is popular in industrial environments because it is openly published and royalty-free.
[src:scada-security/modbus] It was developed for industrial applications, is relatively easy to deploy and maintain compared to other standards, and places few restrictions on the format of the data to be transmitted.
[src:scada-security/modbus] The Modbus protocol uses serial communication lines, Ethernet, or the Internet protocol suite as a transport layer.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Modbus supports communication to and from multiple devices connected to the same cable or Ethernet network.
[src:scada-security/modbus] For example, there can be a device that measures temperature and another device to measure humidity connected to the same cable, both communicating measurements to the same computer, via Modbus.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Modbus is often used to connect a plant/system supervisory computer with a remote terminal unit (RTU) in supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) systems.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Many of the data types are named from industrial control of factory devices, such as ladder logic because of its use in driving relays: a single-bit physical output is called a *coil*, and a single-bit physical input is called a *discrete input* or a *contact*.
[src:scada-security/modbus] It was originally published in 1979 by Modicon (bought by Schneider Electric in 1997).
[src:scada-security/modbus] In 2004, they transferred the rights to the Modbus Organization which is a trade association of users and suppliers of Modbus-compliant devices that advocates for the continued use of the technology.
[src:scada-security/modbus] To support Modbus communication on a network, many modems and gateways incorporate proprietary designs (refer to the diagram: *Architecture of a network for Modbus communication*).
[src:scada-security/modbus] Implementations may deploy either wireline or wireless communication, such as in the ISM radio band, and even Short Message Service (SMS) or General Packet Radio Service (GPRS).
[src:scada-security/modbus] Modbus defines a *client* which is an entity that initiates a transaction to request any specific task from its *request receiver*.
[src:scada-security/modbus] The client's "request receiver", which the client has initiated the transaction with, is then called the *server*.
[src:scada-security/modbus] For example, when a microcontroller connects to a sensor to read its data by Modbus on a wired network, e.g RS485 bus, the MCU in this context is the client and the sensor is the server.
[src:scada-security/modbus] In former terminology, the client was named master and the server named slave.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Modbus defines a protocol data unit (PDU) independently to its lower layer protocols in its protocol stack.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Mapping MODBUS protocol on specific buses or networks requires some additional fields, defined as the application data unit (ADU).
[src:scada-security/modbus] The ADU is formed by a *client* inside a Modbus network when the client initiates a transaction.
[src:scada-security/modbus] The ADU is officially called a *Modbus frame* by the Modbus Organization, although *frame* is used as the data unit in the data-link layer in the OSI and TCP/IP model (while Modbus is an application layer protocol).
[src:scada-security/modbus] ADU max size on RS232/RS485 network is 256 bytes, and with TCP is 260 bytes.
[src:scada-security/modbus] For data encoding, Modbus uses a big-endian representation for addresses and data fields.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Thus, for a 16-bit value, the most significant byte is sent first.
[src:scada-security/modbus] For example, when a 16-bit register has value 0x1234, byte 0x12 is sent before byte 0x34.
[src:scada-security/modbus] The data field of the PDU has the address from 0 to 65535 (not to be confused with the address of the Additional address field of ADU).
[src:scada-security/modbus] The data field of the PDU can be empty, and then has a size of 0.
[src:scada-security/modbus] In this case, the server will not request any information and the function code defines the function to be executed.
[src:scada-security/modbus] If there is no error during the execution process, the data field of the ADU response from server to client will include the data requested, i.e. the data the client previously received.
[src:scada-security/modbus] If there is any error, the server will respond with an exception code.
[src:scada-security/modbus] field's size depends on the function code and usually includes values like variable values, data offset, and sub-function codes.
[src:scada-security/modbus] is equal to the Function code, except that its MSB is set to 1.
[src:scada-security/modbus] For each of the primary tables, the protocol allows individual selection of 65536 data items, and the operations of read or write of those items are designed to span multiple consecutive data items up to a data size limit which is dependent on the transaction function code.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Modbus defines three types of function codes: Public, User-Defined and Reserved.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Note: Some sources use terminology that differs from the standard; for example *Force Single Coil* instead of *Write Single Coil*.
[src:scada-security/modbus] On a successful execution, mb_rsp_pdu will return one byte to note the function code (0x01), followed by one byte to indicate the number of data bytes it is returning (n), which will be the number of coils requested by mb_req_pdu, divided by 8 bits per byte, and rounded up.
[src:scada-security/modbus] The remainder of the response will be the specified number (n) of data bytes.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Starting Address (2 bytes) is 0x0013, (or 19 in decimal) which is the 20th coil.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Quantity of Outputs (2 bytes) is 0x0013, (or 19 in decimal) which corresponds to 19 values of status of coils 20th to 38th.
[src:scada-security/modbus] As 19 coils (20-38) are required, 3 bytes is used to indicate the coil's state.
[src:scada-security/modbus] States of coil from 20 to 27 is 0xCD, which is 1100 1101 in binary.
[src:scada-security/modbus] With coil from 36 to 38, the state will be 0x05, which is 0000 0101.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Coil 38 state is the 3rd bit (count from the right), i.e 1, coil 37 is 0, and coil 36 state is LSb bit, i.e.
[src:scada-security/modbus] User-Defined Function Codes are function codes defined by users.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Modbus gives two range of values for user-defined function codes: 65 to 72 and 100 to 110.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Obviously, user-defined function codes are not unique.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Reserved Function Codes are function codes used by some companies for legacy product and are not available for public use.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Modbus standard also defines Modbus over Serial Line, a protocol over the data link layer of the OSI model for the Modbus application layer protocol to be communicated over a serial bus.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Modbus Serial Line protocol is a master-slave protocol which supports one master and multiple slaves in the serial bus.
[src:scada-security/modbus] With Modbus protocol on the application layer, client/server model is used for the devices on the communication channel.
[src:scada-security/modbus] With Modbus over Serial Line, *client*'s role is implemented by *master*, and the *server*'s role is implemented by *slave*.
[src:scada-security/modbus] The organization's naming convention inverts the common usage of having multiple clients and only one server.
[src:scada-security/modbus] To avoid this confusion, the RS-485 transport layer uses the terms "node" or "device" instead of "server", and the "client" is not a "node".
[src:scada-security/modbus] A serial bus for Modbus over Serial Line can have a maximum of 247 slaves communicating with one master.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Those slaves have a unique address ranging from 1 to 247 (01hex to F7hex).
[src:scada-security/modbus] The addresses from 248 to 255 (F8hex … FFhex) are reserved and must not be used.
[src:scada-security/modbus] The master doesn't need to have an address.
[src:scada-security/modbus] The communication process is initiated by the master, as only it can initiate a Modbus transaction.
[src:scada-security/modbus] A slave will never transmit any data or perform any action without a request from the master, and slaves cannot communicate with each other.
[src:scada-security/modbus] In Modbus over Serial Line, the master initiates requests to the slaves in *unicast* or *broadcast* modes.
[src:scada-security/modbus] In *unicast mode*, the master will initiate a request to a single slave with a specific address.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Upon receiving and finishing the request, the slave will respond with a message to the master.
[src:scada-security/modbus] In this mode, a Modbus transaction includes two messages: one request from the master and one reply from the slave.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Each slave must have a unique address (from 1 to 247) to be addressed independently for the communication.
[src:scada-security/modbus] In *broadcast mode*, the master can send a request to all the slaves, using the broadcast address 0, which is the address reserved for broadcast exchanges (and not the master address).
[src:scada-security/modbus] Slaves must accept broadcast exchanges but must not respond.
[src:scada-security/modbus] The mapping of PDU of Modbus to the serial bus of Modbus over Serial Line protocol results in Modbus Serial Line PDU.
[src:scada-security/modbus] On the physical layer, MODBUS over Serial Line performs its communication on bit by RS485 or RS232, with TIA/EIA-485 Two-Wire interface as the most popular way.
[src:scada-security/modbus] TIA/EIA-232-E (RS232) can also be used but is limited to point-to-point short-range communication.
[src:scada-security/modbus] MODBUS over Serial Line has two transmission modes *RTU* and *ASCII* which are corresponded to two versions of the protocol, known as *Modbus RTU* and *Modbus ASCII*.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Modbus RTU (Remote Terminal Unit), which is the most common implementation available for Modbus, makes use of a compact, binary representation of the data for protocol communication.
[src:scada-security/modbus] The RTU format follows the commands/data with a cyclic redundancy check checksum as an error check mechanism to ensure the reliability of data.
[src:scada-security/modbus] A Modbus RTU message must be transmitted continuously without inter-character hesitations.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Modbus messages are framed (separated) by idle (silent) periods.
[src:scada-security/modbus] The default is even parity, while odd or no parity may be implemented as additional options.
[src:scada-security/modbus] The CRC calculation is widely known as CRC-16-MODBUS, whose polynomial is *x*16 + *x*15 + *x*2 + 1 (normal hexadecimal algebraic polynomial being `8005` and reversed `A001`).
[src:scada-security/modbus] Example of a Modbus RTU frame in hexadecimal: `01 04 02 FF FF B8 80` (CRC-16-MODBUS calculation for the 5 bytes from `01` to `FF` gives `80B8`, which is transmitted least significant byte first).
[src:scada-security/modbus] To ensure frame integrity during the transmission, the time interval between two frames must be at least the transmission time of 3.5 characters, and the time interval between two consecutive characters must be no more than the transmission time of 1.5 characters.
[src:scada-security/modbus] For higher data rates, Modbus RTU recommends to use the fixed values 750 μs for t1.5 and 1.750 ms for t3.5.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Modbus ASCII makes use of ASCII characters (chars) for protocol communication.
[src:scada-security/modbus] The ASCII format uses a longitudinal redundancy check checksum.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Modbus ASCII messages are framed by a leading colon (":", ASCII value 3A16) and trailing newline (CR/LF, ASCII values 0D16 and 0A16).
[src:scada-security/modbus] Modbus ASCII frame do not need to be sent in bursts like Modbus RTU, a delay up to 1 second is permitted between each character transmission by default.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Address, Function, Data, and LRC are ASCII hexadecimal encoded values, whereby each byte (8 bits) of information is encoded as two human-readable ASCII characters from the ranges 0–9 and A–F.
[src:scada-security/modbus] For example, a byte value of 122 (11110102 or 7A16) is encoded as two ASCII characters, "7" and "A", and transmitted as two bytes, `55` (3716, ASCII value for "7") and `65` (4116, ASCII value for "A").
[src:scada-security/modbus] LRC is calculated as the sum of 8-bit values (excluding the start and end characters), negated (two's complement) and encoded as an 8-bit value.
[src:scada-security/modbus] LRC is specified for use only as a checksum: because it is calculated on the encoded data rather than the transmitted characters, its 'longitudinal' characteristic is not available for use with parity bits to locate single-bit errors.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Modbus TCP nomenclature is the same as for the Modbus over Serial line protocol, as any device which send out a Modbus command, is the 'client' and the response comes from a 'server'.
[src:scada-security/modbus] The ADU for Modbus TCP is officially called *Modbus TCP/IP ADU* by the Modbus organization and is also called *Modbus TCP frame* by other parties.
[src:scada-security/modbus] MODBUS Application Protocol header - is the dedicated header used on TCP/IP to identify the MODBUS Application Data Unit.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Data models and function calls are identical for the first four variants listed above; only the encapsulation is different.
[src:scada-security/modbus] However the variants are not interoperable, nor are the frame formats.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Another *de facto* protocol closely related to Modbus appeared later, and was defined by PLC maker April Automates, the result of a collaborative effort between French companies Renault Automation and Merlin Gerin et Cie in 1985: JBUS.
[src:scada-security/modbus] Differences between Modbus and JBUS at that time (number of entities, server stations) are now irrelevant as this protocol almost disappeared with the April PLC series, which AEG Schneider Automation bought in 1994 and then made obsolete.
[src:scada-security/modbus] However, the name JBUS has survived to some extent.
[src:scada-security/scada] The operator interfaces, which enable monitoring and the issuing of process commands, such as controller setpoint changes, are handled through the SCADA computer system.
[src:scada-security/scada] The subordinated operations, e.g. the real-time control logic or controller calculations, are performed by networked modules connected to the field sensors and actuators.
[src:scada-security/scada] The SCADA concept was developed to be a universal means of remote-access to a variety of local control modules, which could be from different manufacturers and allowing access through standard automation protocols.
[src:scada-security/scada] In practice, large SCADA systems have grown to become similar to DCSs in function, while using multiple means of interfacing with the plant.
[src:scada-security/scada] They can control large-scale processes spanning multiple sites, and work over large distances.
[src:scada-security/scada] It is one of the most commonly used types of industrial control systems.
[src:scada-security/scada] The key attribute of a SCADA system is its ability to perform a supervisory operation over a variety of other proprietary devices.
[src:scada-security/scada] Level 1 contains the programmable logic controllers (PLCs) or remote terminal units (RTUs).
[src:scada-security/scada] Level 2 contains the SCADA to readings and equipment status reports that are communicated to level 2 SCADA as required.
[src:scada-security/scada] Data is then compiled and formatted in such a way that a control room operator using the human-machine interface (HMI) can make supervisory decisions to adjust or override normal RTU (PLC) controls.
[src:scada-security/scada] Data may also be fed to a historian, often built on a commodity database management system, to allow trending and other analytical auditing.
[src:scada-security/scada] SCADA systems typically use a *tag database*, which contains data elements called *tags* or *points*, which relate to specific instrumentation or actuators within the process system.
[src:scada-security/scada] Data is accumulated against these unique process control equipment tag references.
[src:scada-security/scada] This is the core of the SCADA system, gathering data on the process and sending control commands to the field connected devices.
[src:scada-security/scada] It refers to the computer and software responsible for communicating with the field connection controllers, which are RTUs and PLCs, and includes the HMI software running on operator workstations.
[src:scada-security/scada] In smaller SCADA systems, the supervisory computer may be composed of a single PC, in which case the HMI is a part of this computer.
[src:scada-security/scada] In larger SCADA systems, the master station may include several HMIs hosted on client computers, multiple servers for data acquisition, distributed software applications, and disaster recovery sites.
[src:scada-security/scada] formation providing continuous control and monitoring in the event of a server malfunction or breakdown.
[src:scada-security/scada] connect to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory computer system.
[src:scada-security/scada] system, using radio, GSM or satellite for communications, and being ruggedised to survive from -20C to +70C or even -40C to +85C without external heating or cooling equipment.
[src:scada-security/scada] PLCs are connected to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory system.
[src:scada-security/scada] In factory automation, PLCs typically have a high speed connection to the SCADA system.
[src:scada-security/scada] In remote applications, such as a large water treatment plant, PLCs may connect directly to SCADA over a wireless link, or more commonly, utilise an RTU for the communications management.
[src:scada-security/scada] For economical reasons, PLCs are often used for remote sites where there is a large I/O count, rather than utilising an RTU alone.
[src:scada-security/scada] This connects the supervisory computer system to the RTUs and PLCs, and may use industry standard or manufacturer proprietary protocols.
[src:scada-security/scada] Both RTUs and PLCs operate autonomously on the near-real time control of the process, using the last command given from the supervisory system.
[src:scada-security/scada] Failure of the communications network does not necessarily stop the plant process controls, and on resumption of communications, the operator can continue with monitoring and control.
[src:scada-security/scada] Some critical systems will have dual redundant data highways, often cabled via diverse routes.
[src:scada-security/scada] The HMI is the operator window of the supervisory system.
[src:scada-security/scada] It presents plant information to the operating personnel graphically in the form of mimic diagrams, which are a schematic representation of the plant being controlled, and alarm and event logging pages.
[src:scada-security/scada] The HMI is linked to the SCADA supervisory computer to provide live data to drive the mimic diagrams, alarm displays and trending graphs.
[src:scada-security/scada] In many installations the HMI is the graphical user interface for the operator, collects all data from external devices, creates reports, performs alarming, sends notifications, etc.
[src:scada-security/scada] Mimic diagrams consist of line graphics and schematic symbols to represent process elements, or may consist of digital photographs of the process equipment overlain with animated symbols.
[src:scada-security/scada] Supervisory operation of the plant is by means of the HMI, with operators issuing commands using mouse pointers, keyboards and touch screens.
[src:scada-security/scada] For example, a symbol of a pump can show the operator that the pump is running, and a flow meter symbol can show how much fluid it is pumping through the pipe.
[src:scada-security/scada] The operator can switch the pump off from the mimic by a mouse click or screen touch.
[src:scada-security/scada] The HMI will show the flow rate of the fluid in the pipe decrease in real time.
[src:scada-security/scada] The HMI package for a SCADA system typically includes a drawing program that the operators or system maintenance personnel use to change the way these points are represented in the interface.
[src:scada-security/scada] These representations can be as simple as an on-screen traffic light, which represents the state of an actual traffic light in the field, or as complex as a multi-projector display representing the position of all of the elevators in a skyscraper or all of the trains on a railway.
[src:scada-security/scada] is a software service within the HMI which accumulates time-stamped data, events, and alarms in a database which can be queried or used to populate graphic trends in the HMI.
[src:scada-security/scada] The historian is a client that requests data from a data acquisition server.
[src:scada-security/scada] An important part of most SCADA implementations is alarm handling.
[src:scada-security/scada] The system monitors whether certain alarm conditions are satisfied, to determine when an alarm event has occurred.
[src:scada-security/scada] Once an alarm event has been detected, one or more actions are taken (such as the activation of one or more alarm indicators, and perhaps the generation of email or text messages so that management or remote SCADA operators are informed).
[src:scada-security/scada] In many cases, a SCADA operator may have to acknowledge the alarm event; this may deactivate some alarm indicators, whereas other indicators remain active until the alarm conditions are cleared.
[src:scada-security/scada] "Smart" RTUs, or standard PLCs, are capable of autonomously executing simple logic processes without involving the supervisory computer.
[src:scada-security/scada] Unlike a procedural language like C or FORTRAN, IEC 61131-3 has minimal training requirements by virtue of resembling historic physical control arrays.
[src:scada-security/scada] This allows SCADA system engineers to perform both the design and implementation of a program to be executed on an RTU or PLC.
[src:scada-security/scada] A programmable automation controller (PAC) is a compact controller that combines the features and capabilities of a PC-based control system with that of a typical PLC.
[src:scada-security/scada] PACs are deployed in SCADA systems to provide RTU and PLC functions.
[src:scada-security/scada] In many electrical substation SCADA applications, "distributed RTUs" use information processors or station computers to communicate with digital protective relays, PACs, and other devices for I/O, and communicate with the SCADA master in lieu of a traditional RTU.
[src:scada-security/scada] Since about 1998, virtually all major PLC manufacturers have offered integrated HMI/SCADA systems, many of them using open and non-proprietary communications protocols.
[src:scada-security/scada] The Remote Terminal Unit (RTU) connects to physical equipment.
[src:scada-security/scada] Typically, an RTU converts the electrical signals from the equipment to digital values.
[src:scada-security/scada] By converting and sending these electrical signals out to equipment the RTU can control equipment.
[src:scada-security/scada] SCADA systems have traditionally used combinations of radio and direct wired connections, although SONET/SDH is also frequently used for large systems such as railways and power stations.
[src:scada-security/scada] The remote management or monitoring function of a SCADA system is often referred to as telemetry.
[src:scada-security/scada] Some users want SCADA data to travel over their pre-established corporate networks or to share the network with other applications.
[src:scada-security/scada] The legacy of the early low-bandwidth protocols remains, though.
[src:scada-security/scada] SCADA protocols are designed to be very compact.
[src:scada-security/scada] Many are designed to send information only when the master station polls the RTU.
[src:scada-security/scada] Typical legacy SCADA protocols include Modbus RTU, RP-570, Profibus and Conitel.
[src:scada-security/scada] These communication protocols, with the exception of Modbus (Modbus has been made open by Schneider Electric), are all SCADA-vendor specific but are widely adopted and used.
[src:scada-security/scada] These communication protocols are standardized and recognized by all major SCADA vendors.
[src:scada-security/scada] Many of these protocols now contain extensions to operate over TCP/IP.
[src:scada-security/scada] Although the use of conventional networking specifications, such as TCP/IP, blurs the line between traditional and industrial networking, they each fulfill fundamentally differing requirements.
[src:scada-security/scada] Network simulation can be used in conjunction with SCADA simulators to perform various 'what-if' analyses.
[src:scada-security/scada] With increasing security demands (such as North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC) and critical infrastructure protection (CIP) in the US), there is increasing use of satellite-based communication.
[src:scada-security/scada] This has the key advantages that the infrastructure can be self-contained (not using circuits from the public telephone system), can have built-in encryption, and can be engineered to the availability and reliability required by the SCADA system operator.
[src:scada-security/scada] Earlier experiences using consumer-grade VSAT were poor.
[src:scada-security/scada] Modern carrier-class systems provide the quality of service required for SCADA.
[src:scada-security/scada] RTUs and other automatic controller devices were developed before the advent of industry wide standards for interoperability.
[src:scada-security/scada] The result is that developers and their management created a multitude of control protocols.
[src:scada-security/scada] Among the larger vendors, there was also the incentive to create their own protocol to "lock in" their customer base.
[src:scada-security/scada] A list of automation protocols is compiled here.
[src:scada-security/scada] An example of efforts by vendor groups to standardize automation protocols is the OPC-UA (formerly "OLE for process control" now Open Platform Communications Unified Architecture).
[src:scada-security/scada] Early SCADA system computing was done by large minicomputers.
[src:scada-security/scada] Common network services did not exist at the time SCADA was developed.
[src:scada-security/scada] Thus SCADA systems were independent systems with no connectivity to other systems.
[src:scada-security/scada] The communication protocols used were strictly proprietary at that time.
[src:scada-security/scada] The first-generation SCADA system redundancy was achieved using a back-up mainframe system connected to all the remote terminal unit sites and was used in the event of failure of the primary mainframe system.
[src:scada-security/scada] Some first generation SCADA systems were developed as "turn key" operations that ran on minicomputers such as the PDP-11 series.
[src:scada-security/scada] SCADA information and command processing were distributed across multiple stations which were connected through a LAN.
[src:scada-security/scada] Information was shared in near real time.
[src:scada-security/scada] Each station was responsible for a particular task, which reduced the cost as compared to first generation SCADA.
[src:scada-security/scada] The network protocols used were still not standardized.
[src:scada-security/scada] Since these protocols were proprietary, very few people beyond the developers knew enough to determine how secure a SCADA installation was.
[src:scada-security/scada] Security of the SCADA installation was usually overlooked.
[src:scada-security/scada] Similar to a distributed architecture, any complex SCADA can be reduced to the simplest components and connected through communication protocols.
[src:scada-security/scada] In the case of a networked design, the system may be spread across more than one LAN network called a process control network (PCN) and separated geographically.
[src:scada-security/scada] Several distributed architecture SCADAs running in parallel, with a single supervisor and historian, could be considered a network architecture.
[src:scada-security/scada] This allows for a more cost-effective solution in very large scale systems.
[src:scada-security/scada] The growth of the internet has led SCADA systems to implement web technologies allowing users to view data, exchange information and control processes from anywhere in the world through standard web protocols such as HTTPS and WebSocket for live updates.
[src:scada-security/scada] The early 2000s saw the proliferation of Web SCADA systems.
[src:scada-security/scada] Web SCADA systems use web browsers such as Google Chrome and Mozilla Firefox as the graphical user interface (GUI) for the operators HMI.
[src:scada-security/scada] This simplifies the client side installation and enables users to access the system from various platforms with web browsers such as servers, personal computers, laptops, tablets and mobile phones.
[src:scada-security/scada] SCADA systems that tie together decentralized facilities such as power, oil, gas pipelines, water distribution and wastewater collection systems were designed to be open, robust, and easily operated and repaired, but not necessarily secure.
[src:scada-security/scada] The move from proprietary technologies to more standardized and open solutions together with the increased number of connections between SCADA systems, office networks and the Internet has made them more vulnerable to types of network attacks that are relatively common in computer security.
[src:scada-security/scada] Security researcher Jerry Brown submitted a similar advisory regarding a buffer overflow vulnerability in a Wonderware InBatchClient ActiveX control.
[src:scada-security/scada] Both vendors made updates available prior to public vulnerability release.
[src:scada-security/scada] Mitigation recommendations were standard patching practices and requiring VPN access for secure connectivity.
[src:scada-security/scada] Consequently, the security of some SCADA-based systems has come into question as they are seen as potentially vulnerable to cyber attacks.
[src:scada-security/scada] SCADA systems are used to control and monitor physical processes, examples of which are transmission of electricity, transportation of gas and oil in pipelines, water distribution, traffic lights, and other systems used as the basis of modern society.
[src:scada-security/scada] The security of these SCADA systems is important because compromise or destruction of these systems would impact multiple areas of society far removed from the original compromise.
[src:scada-security/scada] For example, a blackout caused by a compromised electrical SCADA system would cause financial losses to all the customers that received electricity from that source.
[src:scada-security/scada] Legacy SCADA deployments can remain difficult to secure because control equipment is often geographically distributed, long-lived, and costly to replace or patch.
[src:scada-security/scada] There are many threat vectors to a modern SCADA system.
[src:scada-security/scada] One is the threat of unauthorized access to the control software, whether it is human access or changes induced intentionally or accidentally by virus infections and other software threats residing on the control host machine.
[src:scada-security/scada] Another is the threat of packet access to the network segments hosting SCADA devices.
[src:scada-security/scada] In many cases, the control protocol lacks any form of cryptographic security, allowing an attacker to control a SCADA device by sending commands over a network.
[src:scada-security/scada] In many cases SCADA users have assumed that having a VPN offered sufficient protection, unaware that security can be trivially bypassed with physical access to SCADA-related network jacks and switches.
[src:scada-security/scada] Industrial control vendors suggest approaching SCADA security like Information Security with a defense in depth strategy that leverages common IT practices.
[src:scada-security/scada] Apart from that, research has shown that the architecture of SCADA systems has several other vulnerabilities, including direct tampering with RTUs, communication links from RTUs to the control center, and IT software and databases in the control center.
[src:scada-security/scada] The RTUs could, for instance, be targets of deception attacks injecting false data or denial-of-service attacks.
[src:scada-security/scada] The reliable function of SCADA systems in our modern infrastructure may be crucial to public health and safety.
[src:scada-security/scada] As such, attacks on these systems may directly or indirectly threaten public health and safety.
[src:scada-security/scada] Such an attack has already occurred, carried out on Maroochy Shire Council's sewage control system in Queensland, Australia.
[src:scada-security/scada] Shortly after a contractor installed a SCADA system in January 2000, system components began to function erratically.
[src:scada-security/scada] Pumps did not run when needed and alarms were not reported.
[src:scada-security/scada] More critically, sewage flooded a nearby park and contaminated an open surface-water drainage ditch and flowed 500 meters to a tidal canal.
[src:scada-security/scada] The SCADA system was directing sewage valves to open when the design protocol should have kept them closed.
[src:scada-security/scada] Initially this was believed to be a system bug.
[src:scada-security/scada] Monitoring of the system logs revealed the malfunctions were the result of cyber attacks.
[src:scada-security/scada] Investigators reported 46 separate instances of malicious outside interference before the culprit was identified.
[src:scada-security/scada] The attacks were made by a disgruntled ex-employee of the company that had installed the SCADA system.
[src:scada-security/scada] The ex-employee was hoping to be hired by the utility full-time to maintain the system.
[src:scada-security/scada] In April 2008, the *Commission to Assess the Threat to the United States from Electromagnetic Pulse (EMP) Attack* issued a *Critical Infrastructures Report* document which discussed the extreme vulnerability of SCADA systems to an electromagnetic pulse (EMP) event.
[src:scada-security/scada] After testing and analysis, the commission concluded: "SCADA systems are vulnerable to EMP insult.
[src:scada-security/scada] The large numbers and widespread reliance on such systems by all of the Nation’s critical infrastructures represent a systemic threat to their continued operation following an EMP event.
[src:scada-security/scada] Many vendors of SCADA and control products have begun to address the risks posed by unauthorized access by developing lines of specialized industrial firewall and VPN solutions for TCP/IP-based SCADA networks as well as external SCADA monitoring and recording equipment.
[src:scada-security/scada] The International Society of Automation (ISA) started formalizing SCADA security requirements in 2007 with a working group, WG4.
[src:scada-security/scada] WG4 "deals specifically with unique technical requirements, measurements, and other features required to evaluate and assure security resilience and performance of industrial automation and control systems devices".
[src:scada-security/scada] The increased interest in SCADA vulnerabilities has resulted in vulnerability researchers discovering vulnerabilities in commercial SCADA software and more general offensive SCADA techniques presented to the general security community.
[src:scada-security/scada] In June 2010, anti-virus security company VirusBlokAda reported the first detection of malware that attacks SCADA systems (Siemens' WinCC/PCS 7 systems) running on Windows operating systems.
[src:scada-security/scada] The malware is called Stuxnet and uses four zero-day attacks to install a rootkit which in turn logs into the SCADA's database and steals design and control files.
[src:scada-security/scada] The malware is also capable of changing the control system and hiding those changes.
[src:scada-security/scada] The malware was found on 14 systems, the majority of which were located in Iran.
[src:scada-security/scada] In October 2013 *National Geographic* released a docudrama titled *American Blackout* which dealt with an imagined large-scale cyber attack on SCADA and the United States' electrical grid.
[src:scada-security/scada] Both large and small systems can be built using the SCADA concept.
[src:scada-security/scada] These systems can range from just tens to thousands of control loops, depending on the application.
[src:scada-security/scada] However, SCADA systems may have security vulnerabilities, so the systems should be evaluated to identify risks and solutions implemented to mitigate those risks.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet specifically targets programmable logic controllers (PLCs), which allow the automation of electromechanical processes such as those used to control machinery and industrial processes including gas centrifuges for separating nuclear material.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Exploiting four zero-day flaws in the systems, Stuxnet functions by targeting machines using the Microsoft Windows operating system and networks, then seeking out Siemens Step7 software.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet reportedly compromised Iranian PLCs, collecting information on industrial systems and causing the fast-spinning centrifuges to tear themselves apart.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet's design and architecture are not domain-specific and it could be tailored as a platform for attacking modern SCADA and PLC systems (e.g., in factory assembly lines or power plants), most of which are in Europe, Japan and the United States.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet reportedly destroyed almost one-fifth of Iran's nuclear centrifuges.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Targeting industrial control systems, the worm infected over 200,000 computers and caused 1,000 machines to physically degrade.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet has three modules: a worm that executes all routines related to the main payload of the attack, a link file that automatically executes the propagated copies of the worm and a rootkit component responsible for hiding all malicious files and processes to prevent detection of Stuxnet.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] It is typically introduced to the target environment via an infected USB flash drive, thus crossing any air gap.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The worm then propagates across the network, scanning for Siemens Step7 software on computers controlling a PLC.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In the absence of either criterion, Stuxnet becomes dormant inside the computer.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] If both the conditions are fulfilled, Stuxnet introduces the infected rootkit onto the PLC and Step7 software, modifying the code and giving unexpected commands to the PLC while returning a loop of normal operation system values back to the users.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet, discovered by Sergey Ulasen from a Belarusian antivirus company VirusBlokAda, initially spread via Microsoft Windows, and targeted Siemens industrial control systems.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The worm initially spreads indiscriminately, but includes a highly specialized malware payload that is designed to target only Siemens supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) systems that are configured to control and monitor specific industrial processes.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet infects PLCs by subverting the Step-7 software application that is used to reprogram these devices.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Different variants of Stuxnet targeted five Iranian organizations, with the probable target widely suspected to be uranium enrichment infrastructure in Iran; Symantec noted in August 2010 that 60 percent of the infected computers worldwide were in Iran.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Siemens stated that the worm caused no damage to its customers, but the Iran nuclear program, which uses embargoed Siemens equipment procured secretly, was damaged by Stuxnet.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Kaspersky Lab concluded that the sophisticated attack could only have been conducted "with nation-state support".
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] According to *The Daily Telegraph*, a showreel that was played at a retirement party for the head of the Israel Defense Forces (IDF), Gabi Ashkenazi, included references to Stuxnet as one of his operational successes as the IDF chief of staff.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] On 1 June 2012, an article in *The New York Times* reported that Stuxnet was part of a US and Israeli intelligence operation named *Operation Olympic Games*, devised by the NSA under President George W.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Bush and executed under President Barack Obama.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] On 24 July 2012, an article by Chris Matyszczyk from CNET reported that the Atomic Energy Organization of Iran e-mailed F-Secure's chief research officer Mikko Hyppönen to report a new instance of malware.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] On 25 December 2012, an Iranian semi-official news agency announced there was a cyberattack by Stuxnet, this time on the industries in the southern area of the country.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The malware targeted a power plant and some other industries in Hormozgan province in 2012.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] According to Eugene Kaspersky, the worm also infected a nuclear power plant in Russia.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Kaspersky noted, however, that since the power plant is not connected to the public Internet, the system should remain safe.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The worm was first identified by the security company VirusBlokAda in mid-June 2010.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Journalist Brian Krebs's blog post on 15 July 2010 was the first widely read report on the worm.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The original name given by VirusBlokAda was "Rootkit.Tmphider;" Symantec, however, called it "W32.Temphid", later changing it to "W32.Stuxnet".
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Its current name is derived from a combination of keywords found in the software (".stub" and "mrxnet.sys").
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The timing of the discovery has been attributed to the virus accidentally spreading beyond its intended target due to a programming error introduced in an update.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] This may have caused the worm to spread to an engineer's computer connected to the centrifuges, further propagating when the engineer later connected to the internet at home.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Kaspersky Lab experts initially estimated that Stuxnet began spreading around March or April 2010, but the first variant of the worm appeared in June 2009.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] On 15 July 2010, the day the worm's existence became widely known, a distributed denial-of-service attack targeted the servers of two leading mailing lists on industrial-systems security.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] This attack, from an unknown source but possibly related to Stuxnet, disabled one of the lists, interrupting a key information source for power plants and factories.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Separately, researchers at Symantec uncovered a version of the Stuxnet computer virus that was used to attack Iran's nuclear program in November 2007, with evidence indicating it was under development as early as 2005, when Iran was still setting up its uranium enrichment facility.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The second variant, with substantial improvements, appeared in March 2010, reportedly due to concerns that Stuxnet was not spreading fast enough.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] A third variant, with minor improvements, followed in April 2010.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The worm contains a component with a build timestamp from 3 February 2010.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] On 25 November 2010, Sky News in the United Kingdom reported receiving information from an anonymous source at an unidentified IT security organization claiming that Stuxnet, or a variation of the worm, had been traded on the black market.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In 2015, Kaspersky Lab reported that the Equation Group had used two of the same zero-day attacks prior to their use in Stuxnet, in another malware called fanny.bmp.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Kaspersky Lab noted that "the similar type of usage of both exploits together in different computer worms, at around the same time, indicates that the Equation Group and the Stuxnet developers are either the same or working closely together".
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In 2019, *Chronicle* researchers Juan Andres Guerrero-Saade and Silas Cutler presented findings indicating that at least four distinct threat actor malware platforms collaborated in developing the different versions of Stuxnet.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The collaboration was referred to as 'GOSSIP GIRL', a name derived from a threat group mentioned in classified CSE slides that included Flame.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] GOSSIP GIRL is described as a cooperative umbrella encompassing the Equation Group, Flame, Duqu, and Flowershop (also known as 'Cheshire Cat').
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In 2020, researcher Facundo Muñoz presented findings suggesting that Equation Group may have collaborated with Stuxnet developers in 2009 by providing at least one zero-day exploit, and one exploit from 2008 that was actively used by the Conficker computer worm and Chinese hackers.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In 2017, a group of hackers known as The Shadow Brokers leaked a collection of tools attributed to Equation Group, including new versions of both exploits compiled in 2010.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Analysis of the leaked data indicated significant code overlaps, as both Stuxnet's exploits and Equation Group's exploits were developed using a set of libraries called the "Exploit Development Framework", also leaked by The Shadow Brokers.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Iran was reported to have fortified its cyberwar abilities following the Stuxnet attack, and has been suspected of retaliatory attacks.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] These include attacks against United States banks in the Operation Ababil campaign of 2012-2013, the 2012 Shamoon attack against oil giant Saudi Aramco, and the 2014 strike against Las Vegas Sands Corporation.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Unlike most malware, Stuxnet does little harm to computers and networks that do not meet specific configuration requirements; "The attackers took great care to make sure that only their designated targets were hit ...
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] It was a marksman's job." While the worm is promiscuous, it makes itself inert if Siemens software is not found on infected computers, and contains safeguards to prevent each infected computer from spreading the worm to more than three others, and to erase itself on 24 June 2012.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] For its targets, Stuxnet contains, among other things, code for a man-in-the-middle attack that fakes industrial process control sensor signals so an infected system does not shut down due to detected abnormal behavior.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet attacked Windows systems using an unprecedented four zero-day attacks (plus the CPLINK vulnerability and a vulnerability used by the Conficker worm).
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] It is initially spread using infected removable drives such as USB flash drives, which contain Windows shortcut files to initiate executable code.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The worm then uses other exploits and techniques such as peer-to-peer remote procedure call (RPC) to infect and update other computers inside private networks that are not directly connected to the Internet.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The number of zero-day exploits used is unusual, as they are highly valued and malware creators do not typically make use of (and thus simultaneously make visible) four different zero-day exploits in the same worm.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Amongst these exploits were remote code execution on a computer with Printer Sharing enabled, and the LNK/PIF vulnerability, in which file execution is accomplished when an icon is viewed in Windows Explorer, negating the need for user interaction.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet is unusually large at half a megabyte in size, and written in several different programming languages (including C and C++) which is also irregular for malware.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The Windows component of the malware is promiscuous in that it spreads relatively quickly and indiscriminately.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The driver signing helped it install kernel mode rootkit drivers successfully without users being notified, and thus it remained undetected for a relatively long period of time.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Both compromised certificates have been revoked by Verisign.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Two websites in Denmark and Malaysia were configured as command and control servers for the malware, allowing it to be updated, and for industrial espionage to be conducted by uploading information.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Both of these domain names have subsequently been redirected by their DNS service provider to Dynadot as part of a global effort to disable the malware.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] According to researcher Ralph Langner, once installed on a Windows system, Stuxnet infects project files belonging to Siemens' WinCC/PCS 7 SCADA control software (Step 7), and subverts a key communication library of WinCC called `s7otbxdx.dll`.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Doing so intercepts communications between the WinCC software running under Windows and the target Siemens PLC devices, when the two are connected via a data cable.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The malware is able to modify the code on PLC devices unnoticed, and subsequently to mask its presence from WinCC if the control software attempts to read an infected block of memory from the PLC system.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The malware also used a zero-day exploit in the WinCC/SCADA database software in the form of a hard-coded database password.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet's payload targets only those SCADA configurations that meet criteria that it is programmed to identify.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet requires specific subordinate system to be attached to the targeted Siemens S7-300 controller system: variable-frequency drives (frequency converter drives) and its associated modules.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] It only attacks those PLC systems with variable-frequency drives from two specific vendors: Vacon based in Finland and Fararo Paya based in Iran.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Furthermore, it monitors the frequency of the attached motors, and only attacks systems that spin between 807 Hz and 1,210 Hz.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] This is a much higher frequency than motors typically operate at in most industrial applications, with the notable exception of gas centrifuges.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet installs malware into memory block DB890 of the PLC that monitors the Profibus messaging bus of the system.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] When certain criteria are met, it periodically modifies the frequency to 1,410 Hz and then to 2 Hz and then to 1,064 Hz, and thus affects the operation of the connected motors by changing their rotational speed.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] It also installs a rootkit – the first such documented case on this platform – that hides the malware on the system and masks the changes in rotational speed from monitoring systems.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Siemens has released a detection and removal tool for Stuxnet.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Siemens recommends contacting customer support if an infection is detected and advises installing Microsoft updates for security vulnerabilities and prohibiting the use of third-party USB flash drives.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Siemens also advises immediately upgrading password access codes.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The worm's ability to reprogram external PLCs may complicate the removal procedure.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Symantec's Liam O'Murchu warns that fixing Windows systems may not fully solve the infection; a thorough audit of PLCs may be necessary.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Despite speculation that incorrect removal of the worm could cause damage, Siemens reports that in the first four months since discovery, the malware was successfully removed from the systems of 22 customers without any adverse effects.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Prevention of control system security incidents, such as from viral infections like Stuxnet, is a topic that is being addressed in both the public and the private sector.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The US Department of Homeland Security National Cyber Security Division (NCSD) operates the Control System Security Program (CSSP).
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The program operates a specialized computer emergency response team called the Industrial Control Systems Cyber Emergency Response Team (ICS-CERT), conducts a biannual conference (ICSJWG), provides training, publishes recommended practices, and provides a self-assessment tool.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] As part of a Department of Homeland Security plan to improve American computer security, in 2008 it and the Idaho National Laboratory (INL) worked with Siemens to identify security holes in the company's widely used Process Control System 7 (PCS 7) and its software Step 7.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In July 2008, INL and Siemens publicly announced flaws in the control system at a Chicago conference; Stuxnet exploited these holes in 2009.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Several industry organizations and professional societies have published standards and best practice guidelines providing direction and guidance for control system end-users on how to establish a control system security management program.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The basic premise that all of these documents share is that prevention requires a multi-layered approach, often termed *defense in depth*.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The layers include policies and procedures, awareness and training, network segmentation, access control measures, physical security measures, system hardening, e.g., patch management, and system monitoring, anti-virus and intrusion prevention system (IPS).
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The standards and best practices also all recommend starting with a risk analysis and a control system security assessment.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet may be the largest and costliest development effort in malware history.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Developing its abilities would have required a team of capable programmers, in-depth knowledge of industrial processes, and an interest in attacking industrial infrastructure.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Eric Byres, who has years of experience maintaining and troubleshooting Siemens systems, told *Wired* that writing the code would have taken many man-months, if not man-years.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Symantec estimates that the group developing Stuxnet would have consisted of between five and thirty people, and would have taken six months to prepare.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] *The Guardian*, the BBC and *The New York Times* all claimed that (unnamed) experts studying Stuxnet believe the complexity of the code indicates that only a nation-state would have the abilities to produce it.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The self-destruct and other safeguards within the code implied that a Western government was responsible, or at least is responsible for its development.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] However, software security expert Bruce Schneier initially condemned the 2010 news coverage of Stuxnet as hype, stating that it was almost entirely based on speculation.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] But after subsequent research, Schneier stated in 2012 that "we can now conclusively link Stuxnet to the centrifuge structure at the Natanz nuclear enrichment lab in Iran".
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In late December 2008, Dutch engineer Erik van Sabben travelled to Iran, allegedly to infiltrate the Natanz nuclear facility on behalf of Dutch intelligence and install equipment infected with Stuxnet.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] He died two weeks after the Stuxnet attack at age 36 in an apparent single-vehicle motorcycle accident in Dubai.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Ralph Langner, the researcher who identified that Stuxnet infected PLCs, first speculated publicly in September 2010 that the malware was of Israeli origin, and that it targeted Iranian nuclear facilities.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] However Langner more recently, at a TED conference, recorded in February 2011, stated that "My opinion is that the Mossad is involved, but that the leading force is not Israel.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Langner called the malware "a one-shot weapon" and said that the intended target was probably hit, although he admitted this was speculation.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Another German researcher and spokesman of the German-based Chaos Computer Club, Frank Rieger, was the first to speculate that Natanz was the target.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] On 23 November 2010 it was announced that uranium enrichment at Natanz had ceased several times because of a series of major technical problems.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] A "serious nuclear accident" (supposedly the shutdown of some of its centrifuges) occurred at the site in the first half of 2009, which is speculated to have forced Gholam Reza Aghazadeh, the head of the Atomic Energy Organization of Iran (AEOI), to resign.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Statistics published by the Federation of American Scientists (FAS) show that the number of enrichment centrifuges operational in Iran mysteriously declined from about 4,700 to about 3,900 beginning around the time the nuclear incident WikiLeaks mentioned would have occurred.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The Institute for Science and International Security (ISIS) suggests, in a report published in December 2010, that Stuxnet is a reasonable explanation for the apparent damage at Natanz, and may have destroyed up to 1,000 centrifuges (10 percent) sometime between November 2009 and late January 2010.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The Institute for Science and International Security (ISIS) report further notes that Iranian authorities have attempted to conceal the breakdown by installing new centrifuges on a large scale.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The worm worked by first causing an infected Iranian IR-1 centrifuge to increase from its normal operating speed of 1,064 hertz to 1,410 hertz for 15 minutes before returning to its normal frequency.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Twenty-seven days later, the worm went back into action, slowing the infected centrifuges down to a few hundred hertz for a full 50 minutes.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The stresses from the excessive, then slower, speeds caused the aluminium centrifugal tubes to expand, often forcing parts of the centrifuges into sufficient contact with each other to destroy the machine.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] According to *The Washington Post*, International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) cameras installed in the Natanz facility recorded the sudden dismantling and removal of approximately 900–1,000 centrifuges during the time the Stuxnet worm was reportedly active at the plant.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Iranian technicians, however, were able to quickly replace the centrifuges and the report concluded that uranium enrichment was likely only briefly disrupted.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The Associated Press reported that the semi-official Iranian Students News Agency released a statement on 24 September 2010 stating that experts from the Atomic Energy Organization of Iran met in the previous week to discuss how Stuxnet could be removed from their systems.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] According to analysts, such as David Albright, Western intelligence agencies had been attempting to sabotage the Iranian nuclear program for some time.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The Director of Information Technology Council at the Iranian Ministry of Industries and Mines, Mahmud Liaii, has said that: "An electronic war has been launched against Iran ...
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In response to the infection, Iran assembled a team to combat it.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] With more than 30,000 IP addresses affected in Iran, an official said that the infection was fast spreading in Iran and the problem had been compounded by the ability of Stuxnet to mutate.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Iran had set up its own systems to clean up infections and had advised against using the Siemens SCADA antivirus since it is suspected that the antivirus contains embedded code which updates Stuxnet instead of removing it.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] According to Hamid Alipour, deputy head of Iran's government Information Technology Company, "The attack is still ongoing and new versions of this virus are spreading." He reported that his company had begun the cleanup process at Iran's "sensitive centres and organizations".
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] "We had anticipated that we could root out the virus within one to two months, but the virus is not stable, and since we started the cleanup process three new versions of it have been spreading", he told the Islamic Republic News Agency on 27 September 2010.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] On 29 November 2010, Iranian president Mahmoud Ahmadinejad stated for the first time that a computer virus had caused problems with the controller handling the centrifuges at its Natanz facilities.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] On the same day two Iranian nuclear scientists were targeted in separate, but nearly simultaneous car bomb attacks near Shahid Beheshti University in Tehran.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Majid Shahriari, a quantum physicist, was killed.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Fereydoon Abbasi, a high-ranking official at the Ministry of Defense was seriously wounded.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] *Wired* speculated that the assassinations could indicate that whoever was behind Stuxnet felt that it was not sufficient to stop the nuclear program.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] That same *Wired* article suggested the Iranian government could have been behind the assassinations.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In January 2010, another Iranian nuclear scientist, a physics professor at Tehran University, was killed in a similar bomb explosion.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] On 11 January 2012, a director of the Natanz nuclear enrichment facility, Mostafa Ahmadi Roshan, was killed in an attack quite similar to the one that killed Shahriari.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] An analysis by the FAS demonstrates that Iran's enrichment capacity grew during 2010.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The study indicated that Iran's centrifuges appeared to be performing 60% better than in the previous year, which would significantly reduce Tehran's time to produce bomb-grade uranium.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The FAS report was reviewed by an official with the IAEA who affirmed the study.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] European and US officials, along with private experts, told Reuters that Iranian engineers were successful in neutralizing and purging Stuxnet from their country's nuclear machinery.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Given the growth in Iranian enrichment ability in 2010, the country may have intentionally put out misinformation to cause Stuxnet's creators to believe that the worm was more successful in disabling the Iranian nuclear program than it actually was.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Israel, through Unit 8200, has been speculated to be the country behind Stuxnet in multiple media reports and by experts such as Richard A.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Falkenrath, former Senior Director for Policy and Plans within the US Office of Homeland Security.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Israel has not publicly commented on the Stuxnet attack but in 2010 confirmed that cyberwarfare was now among the pillars of its defense doctrine, with a military intelligence unit set up to pursue both defensive and offensive options.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] When questioned whether Israel was behind the virus in the fall of 2010, some Israeli officials broke into "wide smiles", fueling speculation that the government of Israel was involved with its genesis.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] American presidential advisor Gary Samore also smiled when Stuxnet was mentioned, although American officials have suggested that the virus originated abroad.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In 2009, a year before Stuxnet was discovered, Scott Borg of the United States Cyber-Consequences Unit (US-CCU) suggested that Israel may prefer to mount a cyberattack rather than a military strike on Iran's nuclear facilities.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In late 2010 Borg stated: "Israel certainly has the ability to create Stuxnet and there is little downside to such an attack because it would be virtually impossible to prove who did it.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] So a tool like Stuxnet is Israel's obvious weapon of choice." Iran uses P-1 centrifuges at Natanz, the design for which A.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Khan stole in 1976 and took to Pakistan.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] His black market nuclear-proliferation network sold P-1s to, among other customers, Iran.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Experts believe that Israel also somehow acquired P-1s and tested Stuxnet on the centrifuges, installed at the Dimona facility that is part of its own nuclear program.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The equipment may be from the United States, which received P-1s from Libya's former nuclear program.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Some have also cited several clues in the code such as a concealed reference to the word *MYRTUS*, believed to refer to the Latin name *myrtus* of the Myrtle tree, which in Hebrew is called *hadassah*.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Hadassah was the birth name of the former Jewish queen of Persia, Queen Esther.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] However, it may be that the "MYRTUS" reference is simply a misinterpreted reference to SCADA components known as *RTUs* (Remote Terminal Units) and that this reference is actually "My RTUs"–a management feature of SCADA.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Also, the number 19790509 appears once in the code and may refer to the date *1979 May 09*, the day Habib Elghanian, a Persian Jew, was executed in Tehran.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Another date that appears in the code is "24 September 2007", the day that Iran's president Mahmoud Ahmadinejad spoke at Columbia University and made comments questioning the validity of the Holocaust.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Such data is not conclusive, since, as noted by Symantec, "attackers would have the natural desire to implicate another party".
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] There has also been several reports on the involvement of the United States and its collaboration with Israel, with one report stating that "there is vanishingly little doubt that [it] played a role in creating the worm".
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] It has been reported that the United States, under one of its most secret programs, initiated by the Bush administration and accelerated by the Obama administration, has sought to destroy Iran's nuclear program by novel methods such as undermining Iranian computer systems.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] A leaked diplomatic cable showed how the United States was advised to target Iran's nuclear abilities through 'covert sabotage'.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] An article in *The New York Times* in January 2009 credited a then-unspecified program with preventing an Israeli military attack on Iran where some of the efforts focused on ways to destabilize the centrifuges.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] A *Wired* article claimed that Stuxnet "is believed to have been created by the United States".
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Dutch historian Peter Koop speculated that the Tailored Access Operations could have developed Stuxnet, possibly in collaboration with Israel.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Bumgarner pointed out that the centrifuges used to process fuel for nuclear weapons are a key target for *cybertage* operations and that they can be made to destroy themselves by manipulating their rotational speeds.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Hayden said: "There are those out there who can take a look at this ... and maybe even attempt to turn it to their own purposes".
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In the same report, Sean McGurk, a former cybersecurity official at the Department of Homeland Security noted that the Stuxnet source code could now be downloaded online and modified to be directed at new target systems.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Speaking of the Stuxnet creators, he said: "They opened the box.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In April 2011, Iranian government official Gholam Reza Jalali stated that an investigation had concluded that the United States and Israel were behind the Stuxnet attack.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Frank Rieger stated that three European countries' intelligence agencies agreed that Stuxnet was a joint United States-Israel effort.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The code for the Windows injector and the PLC payload differ in style, likely implying collaboration.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Other experts believe that a US-Israel cooperation is unlikely because "the level of trust between the two countries' intelligence and military establishments is not high".
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] A *Wired* magazine article about US General Keith B.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Alexander stated: "And he and his cyber warriors have already launched their first attack.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] China, Jordan, and France are other possibilities, and Siemens may have also participated.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Langner speculated that the infection may have spread from USB drives belonging to Russian contractors since the Iranian targets were not accessible via the Internet.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In 2019, it was reported that an Iranian mole working for Dutch intelligence at the behest of Israel and the CIA inserted the Stuxnet virus with a USB flash drive or convinced another person working at the Natanz facility to do so.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Sandro Gaycken from the Free University Berlin argued that the attack on Iran was a ruse to distract from Stuxnet's real purpose.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] According to him, its broad dissemination in more than 100,000 industrial plants worldwide suggests a field test of a cyber weapon in different security cultures, testing their preparedness, resilience, and reactions, all highly valuable information for a cyberwar unit.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The United Kingdom has denied involvement in the worm's creation.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In July 2013, Edward Snowden claimed that Stuxnet was cooperatively developed by the United States and Israel.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] According to a report by Reuters, the NSA also tried to sabotage North Korea's nuclear program using a version of Stuxnet.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The operation was reportedly launched in tandem with the attack that targeted Iranian centrifuges in 2009–10.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The North Korean nuclear program shares a number of similarities with the Iranian, both having been developed with technology transferred by Pakistani nuclear scientist A.Q.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The effort failed, however, because North Korea's extreme secrecy and isolation made it impossible to introduce Stuxnet into the nuclear facility.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In 2018, Gholamreza Jalali, Iran's chief of the National Organization for Passive Defense, claimed that his country fended off a Stuxnet-like attack targeting the country's telecom infrastructure.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Iran's Telecommunications minister, Mohammad-Javad Azari Jahromi has since accused Israel of orchestrating the attack.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Iran plans to sue Israel through the International Court of Justice (ICJ) and is also willing to launch a retaliation attack if Israel does not desist.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] A November 2013 article in Foreign Policy magazine claims existence of an earlier, much more sophisticated attack on the centrifuge complex at Natanz, focused on increasing centrifuge failure rate over a long time period by stealthily inducing uranium hexafluoride gas overpressure incidents.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] This malware was capable of spreading only by being physically installed, probably by previously contaminated field equipment used by contractors working on Siemens control systems within the complex.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] It is not clear whether this attack attempt was successful, but follow-up by a different, simpler, and more conventional attack is indicative that it was not.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] On 1 September 2011, a new worm was found, thought to be related to Stuxnet.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The Laboratory of Cryptography and System Security (CrySyS) of the Budapest University of Technology and Economics analyzed the malware, naming the threat **Duqu**.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Symantec, based on this report, continued the analysis of the threat, calling it "nearly identical to Stuxnet, but with a completely different purpose", and published a detailed technical paper.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The main component used in Duqu is designed to capture information such as keystrokes and system information.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] The exfiltrated data may be used to enable a future Stuxnet-like attack.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] On 28 December 2011, Kaspersky Lab's director of global research and analysis spoke to Reuters about recent research results showing that the platform Stuxnet and Duqu both originated in 2007, and is being referred to as Tilded due to the ~d at the beginning of the file names.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Also uncovered in this research was the possibility for three more variants based on the Tilded platform.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In May 2012, the new malware "Flame" was found, thought to be related to Stuxnet.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Researchers named the program "Flame" after the name of one of its modules.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] After analysing the code of Flame, Kaspersky Lab said that there is a strong relationship between Flame and Stuxnet.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] An early version of Stuxnet contained code to propagate infections via USB drives that is nearly identical to a Flame module that exploits the same vulnerability.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Since 2010, there has been extensive international news media coverage on Stuxnet and its aftermath.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In early commentary, *The Economist* pointed out that Stuxnet was "a new kind of cyber-attack".
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] On 8 July 2011, *Wired* then published an article detailing how network security experts were able to decipher the origins of Stuxnet.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In that piece, Kim Zetter claimed that Stuxnet's "cost–benefit ratio is still in question".
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Later commentators tended to focus on the strategic significance of Stuxnet as a cyber weapon.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Following the Wired piece, Holger Stark called Stuxnet the "first digital weapon of geopolitical importance, it could change the way wars are fought".
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Meanwhile, Eddie Walsh referred to Stuxnet as "the world's newest high-end asymmetric threat".
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Ultimately, some claim that the "extensive media coverage afforded to Stuxnet has only served as an advertisement for the vulnerabilities used by various cybercriminal groups".
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] While that may be the case, the media coverage has also increased awareness of cyber security threats.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Alex Gibney's 2016 documentary *Zero Days* covers the phenomenon around Stuxnet.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] A zero-day (also known as 0-day) vulnerability is a computer-software vulnerability that is unknown to, or unaddressed by, those who should be interested in mitigating the vulnerability (including the vendor of the target software).
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Until the vulnerability is mitigated, hackers can exploit it to adversely affect computer programs, data, additional computers or a network.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] In 2016, it was revealed that General James Cartwright, the former head of the U.S.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Strategic Command, had leaked information related to Stuxnet.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] He later pleaded guilty for lying to FBI agents pursuing an investigation into the leak.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] On 17 January 2017, he was granted a full pardon in this case by President Obama, thus expunging his conviction.
[src:scada-security/stuxnet] Darknet Diaries' Podcast episode Stuxnet, discusses Stuxnet with guest Kim Zetter and references the book Count Down to Zero Day.
